 - Analog Twin: Keeping pen and paper offices alive for resilience
+  - More and more institutions are moving to fully digital-only/"paperless" operations
+  - Backup systems exist, but are increasingly brittle and usually depend on some form of internet to exist
+  - 3-2-1 backup strategy (three copies of data including original, two different forms of media, one copy off-site) usually imply _digital_ media as the backup
+  - Adding an analog twin - an automatically replicated analog version of all data stored in the digital version - can help add an additional level of "collapse-proofing"
+  - Pen and paper offices and regular postal delivery have worked for centuries, and we know they are somewhat resilient to system collapse in a way that digital systems are not
+  - Analog backup format is based on the same gazette system that has powered government in lots of places for centuries (change sets on paper that can be serially to update a local copy of a database)
+  - Analog Twin is pointed at e.g. a WebDAV share or local folder, watches for changes, and continously prints new pages for the Gazette
+  - Gazette can then be stored in binders just as the old pen and paper offices did whenever there is time
+  - In the case of network collapse, members can fall back to the analog versions and continue functioning
+  - Also super useful for private persons, e.g. for backing up all the data in that "important" folder with all of your passwords, 2FA recovery codes, SIN numbers, copies of passports and tax information etc.
+  - Still in early days, still brainstorming this together with a librarian friend who knows much more about the analog part of this than me
